  "prompt": "How do you sort a collection in Java?",
  "response": "In Java, there are several ways to sort a collection. The most common approach is to use the `Collections` utility class for sorting lists, and the `Stream` API for sorting other types of collections or in a more functional style. Below are some examples demonstrating how to sort a collection in Java:\n\n### 1. Sorting a List Using `Collections.sort()`\n\nYou can use `Collections.sort()` to sort a `List`. Here\u2019s an example:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.ArrayList;\nimport java.util.Collections;\nimport java.util.List;\n\npublic class SortListExample {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();\n        list.add(\"Banana\");\n        list.add(\"Apple\");\n        list.add(\"Cherry\");\n\n        // Sort the list in natural order\n        Collections.sort(list);\n\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted list: \" + list);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### 2. Sorting a List with a Custom Comparator\n\nIf you need to sort the list in a custom order, you can pass a `Comparator` to `Collections.sort()`:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.ArrayList;\nimport java.util.Collections;\nimport java.util.Comparator;\nimport java.util.List;\n\npublic class SortListWithComparator {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();\n        list.add(\"Banana\");\n        list.add(\"Apple\");\n        list.add(\"Cherry\");\n\n        // Sort the list in reverse order\n        Collections.sort(list, Comparator.reverseOrder());\n\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted list in reverse order: \" + list);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Using `List.sort()` Method\n\nJava 8 introduced the `List.sort()` method which can also accept a `Comparator`:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.ArrayList;\nimport java.util.List;\n\npublic class SortListMethod {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();\n        list.add(\"Banana\");\n        list.add(\"Apple\");\n        list.add(\"Cherry\");\n\n        // Sort the list in natural order\n        list.sort(String::compareTo);\n\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted list: \" + list);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### 4. Sorting a Set Using `TreeSet`\n\nIf you are working with a `Set`, you can use a `TreeSet`, which maintains a sorted order:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.Set;\nimport java.util.TreeSet;\n\npublic class SortSetExample {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Set<String> set = new TreeSet<>();\n        set.add(\"Banana\");\n        set.add(\"Apple\");\n        set.add(\"Cherry\");\n\n        // The set will be sorted automatically\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted set: \" + set);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### 5. Using Streams to Sort\n\nYou can also use the Java Stream API to sort a collection:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.Arrays;\nimport java.util.List;\nimport java.util.stream.Collectors;\n\npublic class SortWithStreams {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        List<String> list = Arrays.asList(\"Banana\", \"Apple\", \"Cherry\");\n        \n        List<String> sortedList = list.stream()\n                                       .sorted()\n                                       .collect(Collectors.toList());\n\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted list using streams: \" + sortedList);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThese are some of the most common ways to sort collections in Java. Depending on your needs\u2014whether you are working with lists or sets, or want a specific sorting order\u2014you can choose the appropriate method to sort your collection.",
